arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
Daily Trench Journal

Area F, Trench 7

June 13, 2005

C. Painter

Today began by leveling with trowels in L7173 in the western half of the trench. This work brought to light several new features including a small mud brick wall, medium-sized circular pit with ash and what appears to be a small brick-lined burial containing a small child. This assessment is based on the cranial size and teeth, though the skeleton itself is disturbed and poorly preserved. I decided to wait and open these loci tomorrow as today has more pressing concerns, namely the removal of structure 7178.

This was done wall by wall as the course number varies between them. First, single-course wall A was excavated, then two course wall B, a very thin course that was remaining of wall C and finally a thicker course for wall D. Refer to the Day Plan for June 13, 2005 to see the wall name designations. The subwall fill locus was assigned L7195, a light brown (7.5 YR 6/3) medium to coarse compacted clay that was also excavated with hand picks and trowels.

The area in 7191 directly between bin/pit 7186 and 7178 was also scraped and cleaned in order to look one last time for any direct connection between structure 7178 and the bin 7186. This was not achieved however I still believe, based on the proximity and elevations, that both pit 7181 and pit/bin 7186 are associated with structure 7178.

The interior portion of pit L7181 was also closed today after excavation of the western portion. Two soil samples were collected (KT16, 17) and the sides of the pit scraped to ensure that the edges of the pit has been reached. This trowel scraping revealed a distinct ash layer visible in the west and northwest/north section profile from which a carbon sample was able to be extracted (KT18). This ash layer was not visible during excavation of the pit and can be considered a subdivision within the locus.

The interior of locus 7181 was closed at a depth of roughly 80cm despite the fact that the soil on the bottom is still relatively soft though slightly more compact than the uppermost levels of the pit. Therefore it is possible that the pit may continue, however at this juncture it is critical that all my workmen be available to excavate in the new architectural features that will be explore tomorrow and in the coming week(s). However the burnt mud bricks that line pit 7181 were left in place for this time and will be removed at a later date.

Last, the final surface (7194) in the northwest corner of the trench between walls 7163 and 7154 was opened and excavated using the Household Archaeology Protocol (HAP). This very pale brown (10 YR 7/4) and gray (10 YR 5/1) surface was highly compacted and whether or not it is bonded to either wall 7163 or 7154 is very unclear. The relative unevenness and ash-heavy eastern end led me to believe that 7194 is not so much a plastered floor as a compacted surface.

Below 7194 a subsurface fill (7196) was opened and also excavated with a large pick. This pink (7.5 YR 7/3) and greenish gray (Gley I 6/5GY) medium to coarse fill had medium compaction and again heavy ashy inclusions on the eastern side. The locus was excavated down to the level of the bottom of closed pit 7162 at which point in the very center of the locus a medium-sized vessel was uncovered in situ and standing upright. This vessel was left and will be explored tomorrow.
